      <h1 class="title">Vitamin D Deficiency in Dubai: Why Testing Matters</h1>

      <div class="blog-content">
        <h4>Introduction</h4>
        <p>
          It sounds like a contradiction: Dubai is drenched in sunshine nearly every day, but over
          <b>80% of residents</b>—locals and expats—are vitamin D deficient. Many spend time
          outside, yet their levels still fall short. This is the “Dubai vitamin D paradox.” In this
          guide, we explain why sunshine isn’t always enough, who’s most at risk, and why testing is
          vital—even if you feel healthy.
        </p>

        <h4>What Is Vitamin D and Why Does It Matter?</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Helps absorb calcium → strong bones and teeth</li>
          <li>Supports immunity and reduces risk of infections</li>
          <li>Plays a role in energy, mood, and depression prevention</li>
          <li>Improves muscle strength and balance</li>
          <li>May support fertility and hormone health</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Low vitamin D can cause frequent illness, fatigue, and weak bones. In the long run, it
          raises the risk of osteoporosis, poor immunity, and mood changes.
        </p>

