        <h4>The Desert Paradox: Why Dubai Residents Still Get Deficient</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <b>Indoor lifestyle:</b> Air-conditioned homes, offices, and malls block UVB rays.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Clothing &amp; cultural habits:</b> Many cover most of their skin, limiting exposure.
          </li>
          <li><b>Sunscreen use:</b> Protects from burns but also blocks vitamin D synthesis.</li>
          <li>
            <b>Skin tone &amp; obesity:</b> Darker skin and higher body fat reduce vitamin D
            availability.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h4>UAE Prevalence: What the Studies Show</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><b>2025 meta-analysis:</b> 80%+ of healthy adults had low or deficient vitamin D.</li>
          <li><b>2022 Abu Dhabi study:</b> 44% deficient, only 20% above 32 ng/mL.</li>
          <li><b>2024 UAE review:</b> National deficiency rates may be as high as 90%.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          This affects all ages, genders, and nationalities. Deficiency is common even in summer due
          to time spent indoors.
        </p>

        <h4>Why This Matters: The Risks of Low Vitamin D</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Weak bones → higher fracture risk</li>
          <li>Muscle cramps and more frequent falls</li>
          <li>Lowered immunity → more infections</li>
          <li>Increased risk of diabetes, high blood pressure, and cancers</li>
          <li>Mood swings, depression, fatigue</li>
          <li>Possible link to women’s reproductive health</li>
        </ul>

