        <h4>What to Do If Your Levels Are Low</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><b>Below 20:</b> Supplements, diet changes, supervised sun exposure</li>
          <li><b>20–30:</b> Annual testing + lifestyle adjustments</li>
          <li><b>30–50:</b> Maintain with sun &amp; balanced diet</li>
          <li><b>Over 100:</b> Too high—stop supplements, see doctor</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>How to Boost Vitamin D Levels Safely</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><b>Sun:</b> 10–30 min midday, 2–3x weekly (avoid burning)</li>
          <li><b>Food:</b> Salmon, sardines, eggs, fortified milk, UV-exposed mushrooms</li>
          <li><b>Supplements:</b> D3 preferred; usually 1,000–2,000 IU/day</li>
          <li><b>Follow-up:</b> Retest after 8–12 weeks</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>When to Seek Professional Advice</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Persistent fatigue, mood changes, or frequent illness</li>
          <li>Chronic bone pain, muscle weakness, or fractures</li>
          <li>Absorption issues (celiac, liver, or kidney disease)</li>
          <li>Medications like steroids or anticonvulsants</li>
        </ul>

